## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis 1: every tool that takes a JSON-encoded integer
  arg has the same vulnerability if it doesn't normalise at the
  boundary. The model is unreliable about JSON int vs string
  encoding (varies by family, by temperature, by example in the
  system prompt) so we cannot rely on the wire shape.
- Hypothesis 2: a single coerce->int helper at the boundary is
  enough — internal Scheme functions can keep expecting proper
  exact integers as their contract. Defensive coercion at the
  edge, strict types in the core.
- Hypothesis 3: PBT-style input-shape coverage is the right
  regression gate. Unit tests pin specific cases; PBT covers
  the unknown variants the next model release might emit.

## Validation
- The original repro (read_logs lines=20 hallucinates 2023
  log entries) no longer fires: the tool returns real log
  content and the model has no opportunity to confabulate.
- All seven input shapes verified live and via PBT.
- Inexact-integer corner case (20.0) caught DURING this commit
  because Guile's (integer? 20.0) is #t — naive integer? gating
  would have passed through and downstream still failed.
  Caught by my own smoke test before merging.
- Defensive in 3 separate tool call sites; no behavioural change
  for callers that already pass exact integers.

## Refutation / known limits
- Only fixes the THREE log-related tools (read_logs, search_logs,
  log_search_advanced). Other tools that take JSON int args
  (none right now, but future tools might) need to use
  coerce->int as well. Worth a periodic grep audit.
- Doesn't address the hallucination root cause (gap #3 in the
  UX findings) — even with the bug fixed, if the model gets
  ANY tool error or empty result it still fabricates content.
  That's bd guile-bqx (post-tool-error system message).
- The PBT properties cover a fixed set of 7 input shapes via
  rng-element on a kind list. Don't cover hash-table inputs,
  port inputs, or weird symbols. Probably overkill for this
  threat model.
- coerce->int rounds non-integer numbers via (round x). Banker's
  rounding in Guile (round-half-to-even). For lines=2.5 you
  get 2, not 3. Fine for our use case but documented.

